<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[189,310,1315,1341]" box="[189,310,1315,1341]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,1315,1341]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,1315,1341]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[189,1399,1364,1648]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Large, predominantly black and long black pilose pipizine; thorax black, extensively black pilose; wing brown infuscated; cell c wide; legs black with long pilose tarsi and metaleg; terga II and III with large rectangular brownish antero-lateral maculae; genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[852,925,1438,1464]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[189,232,1879,1905]" captionTargetBox="[238,1369,923,1815]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[189,1401,893,1839]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 2. Trichopsomyia pilosa sp. nov., male genitalia, holotype (NHMUK 010864268). A. Lateral view. B. Epandrium, dorsal view. C. Apical part of hypandrium, ventral view. Scale bars = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3954992" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3954992/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) epandrium elongate; surstylus bilobed with rather long baso-dorsal process and with very long, elongate and slightly sickle-shaped narrow, elongate ventral process; hypoproct (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Downes M. F. &amp; Skevington J. H. &amp; Thompson F. C." box="[662,887,1511,1538]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Downes" journalOrPublisher="Australian Entomologist" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" pagination="29 - 38" part="44" refId="ref4903" refString="Downes M. F., Skevington J. H. &amp; Thompson F. C. 2017. A new ant inquiline flower fly (Diptera: Syrphidae: Pipizinae) from Australia. Australian Entomologist 44 (1): 29 - 38." title="A new ant inquiline flower fly (Diptera: Syrphidae: Pipizinae) from Australia" type="journal article" year="2017">
Downes 
<emphasis box="[764,822,1511,1537]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">et al.</emphasis>
2017
</bibRefCitation>
) mushroom shaped, shaft on ventral surface densely but short pilose; hypandrium narrow, elongate with elongate rectangular process; postgonite (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Downes M. F. &amp; Skevington J. H. &amp; Thompson F. C." box="[245,478,1585,1612]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Downes" journalOrPublisher="Australian Entomologist" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" pagination="29 - 38" part="44" refId="ref4903" refString="Downes M. F., Skevington J. H. &amp; Thompson F. C. 2017. A new ant inquiline flower fly (Diptera: Syrphidae: Pipizinae) from Australia. Australian Entomologist 44 (1): 29 - 38." title="A new ant inquiline flower fly (Diptera: Syrphidae: Pipizinae) from Australia" type="journal article" year="2017">
Downes 
<emphasis box="[349,410,1585,1611]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">et al.</emphasis>
2017
</bibRefCitation>
) dome-shaped in lateral view, with several small tooth in two rows on apicoventral surface.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[189,324,1690,1716]" box="[189,324,1690,1716]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,1690,1716]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,1690,1716]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[189,1399,1738,1838]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">The specific epithet ʻpilosaʼ, the Latin word for ʻhairyʼ, refers to the extensively and long pilose katepisternum, the long pili on the metasternum and especially the long pilose metatibia. The name is to be treated as an adjective.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
